3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Phemex calculates funding rates using a time-weighted average premium over the 8-hour period, sampled every minute during the final hour before settlement. Long positions pay funding to shorts when rates are positive, indicating perpetual trading above spot price. The exchange's funding rate formula incorporates both premium and interest rate components, with the latter typically set at 0.01% per 8-hour period. Settlement occurs precisely at funding times, with positions automatically debited or credited based on notional size."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ETH","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETH/USDT on Phemex represents one of the most liquid perpetual contracts outside Binance and Bybit, making it ideal for funding rate arbitrage strategies. The pair's consistent volume and Phemex's competitive 0.01% maker fees create favorable conditions for delta-neutral positions. Ethereum's established institutional interest generates predictable funding patterns, particularly during major market events and ETF trading hours."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ETH/USDT funding rates on Phemex have averaged 0.02% per 8-hour period over the past year, with notable spikes above 0.1% during major rally phases. The contract typically experiences negative funding during sharp market corrections, reaching -0.15% during the May 2024 deleveraging event. Weekend funding rates tend to be more volatile due to reduced institutional activity, with Friday evening UTC often showing elevated positive rates. Cross-referencing with traditional market hours reveals higher funding rates during US trading sessions, particularly around options expiry dates."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Phemex's 8-hour funding cycle creates systematic arbitrage opportunities when rates diverge significantly from competing exchanges like Binance or Bybit. The exchange's lower maker fees (0.01% vs 0.02% industry standard) provide additional edge for market-making strategies around funding settlements. Calendar arbitrage works particularly well on ETH/USDT, taking advantage of predictable rate patterns around Ethereum network upgrades and quarterly futures expiry dates. Advanced traders exploit Phemex's precise UTC settlement timing by entering positions 15-30 minutes before funding to capture rate predictions while minimizing directional exposure."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Phemex's smaller user base compared to tier-1 exchanges creates occasional liquidity gaps, particularly during high volatility periods when funding rates are most attractive. The exchange's automatic deleveraging system can force position closures during extreme market stress, disrupting long-term funding strategies. Regulatory uncertainty in Singapore and potential restrictions on retail leverage could impact contract specifications without advance notice. Cross-exchange arbitrage faces settlement risk, as Phemex's 8-hour cycle may not align perfectly with competitors, creating basis risk between funding collection and hedging execution."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"What time does ETH/USDT funding settle on Phemex?","answer":"Funding settlements occur every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC precisely. Phemex calculates the final rate during the last hour before settlement, so positions held at settlement time will pay or receive funding based on their notional size."},{"question":"How does Phemex's ETH/USDT funding compare to other exchanges?","answer":"Phemex typically trades within 0.01-0.02% of Binance and Bybit rates, but can diverge during high volatility. The 8-hour cycle versus others' hourly cycles means rates are generally more stable but less responsive to short-term sentiment shifts."},{"question":"Can I hedge ETH/USDT funding positions on Phemex with spot?","answer":"Yes, Phemex offers ETH spot trading for delta-neutral strategies. However, the spot market has lower liquidity than perpetuals, so large hedging orders should be split to avoid slippage during funding collection periods."},{"question":"What's the maximum funding rate on Phemex ETH/USDT?","answer":"Phemex caps funding rates at ±0.375% per 8-hour period (equivalent to ±1.125% daily). During extreme market conditions, rates will hit these limits rather than exceeding them, which can create arbitrage opportunities versus uncapped exchanges."}]}]
